---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import ShiftDifferentialCalculator from '../../components/calculator/ShiftDifferentialCalculator.astro';
import Card from '../../components/ui/Card.astro';

const breadcrumbs = [
  { label: 'Home', path: '/' },
  { label: 'Calculators', path: '/all-calculators' },
  { label: 'Shift Differential Calculator', path: '/calculator/shift-differential-calculator' }
];
---

<Layout
  title="Shift Differential Calculator - Calculate Premium Shift Pay & Taxes"
  description="Free online Shift Differential Calculator. Calculate regular earnings, night/evening premiums, weekend bonuses, tax deductions, and blended effective hourly rates."
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
>
  <div class="calculator-page-container container">
    <!-- Interactive Component Slot -->
    <ShiftDifferentialCalculator />

    <!-- Guide Content Section -->
    <div class="calculator-guide-section" style="margin-top: var(--space-12);">
      
      <!-- Prominent Blog Post Cross-Link Card -->
      <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
        <Card elevation="sm" style="border: 1.5px solid var(--color-primary); background-color: var(--color-bg-base); padding: var(--space-5);">
          <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--space-2);">
            <span style="font-size: 0.8rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-primary); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em;">Featured Shift Premium Case Study</span>
            <h3 style="margin: 0; font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 800;">Working the Night Shift: How Blended Shift Differentials Boosted My Take-Home Pay</h3>
            <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); line-height: 1.5;">
              Read the first-person story of a warehouse logistics operator who volunteered for night and weekend shifts, leveraging a flat-rate night premium and percentage-based weekend bonuses to increase their effective hourly rate.
            </p>
            <a href="/blog/understanding-shift-differential-pay" style="font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.95rem; color: var(--color-primary); margin-top: var(--space-2); display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 4px; width: fit-content; text-decoration: underline;">
              Read: How to Calculate Shift Differential Pay & Blended Rates
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"></line><polyline points="12 5 19 12 12 19"></polyline></svg>
            </a>
          </div>
        </Card>
      </div>

      <div class="prose">
        <h2>What is Shift Differential Pay?</h2>
        <p>
          In employment accounting and human resource management, <strong>shift differential pay</strong> is the premium compensation workers receive for working shifts outside standard business hours. It is commonly offered for evening shifts, night shifts, weekend shifts, or holiday schedules to offset the inconvenience of working unsocial hours.
        </p>
        <p>
          Unlike overtime pay, which is legally mandated for working more than 40 hours a week, shift differentials are offered voluntarily by employers to attract talent for less desirable shifts.
        </p>

        <h2>How This Calculator Works (Step-by-Step)</h2>
        <p>
          To compute your total gross earnings, taxes, and blended rates, follow these steps:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Select Your Currency:</strong> Choose your local currency from the dropdown menu (e.g. USD, EUR, INR) to format all input fields and results correctly.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Input Regular Parameters:</strong> Enter your Regular Base Hourly Rate and standard dayshift hours worked (typically 40 hours).
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Configure Shift 1 Premium (e.g. Nights):</strong> Select whether your night premium is a Flat Rate ($/hr) or a Percentage (%), enter the premium value, and input the hours worked.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Configure Shift 2 Premium (e.g. Weekends):</strong> Select whether your weekend premium is a Flat Rate ($/hr) or a Percentage (%), enter the premium value, and input the hours worked.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Configure Taxes:</strong> Enter your combined estimated tax rate (federal, state, and local withholdings) to calculate net take-home pay.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Review the Outputs:</strong> The calculator instantly displays your total gross pay, net take-home earnings, blended effective hourly rate, and a detailed breakdown of your standard and premium earnings.
          </li>
        </ol>

        <h2>The Mathematics of Shift Differentials</h2>
        <p>
          The calculator applies standard payroll formulas to isolate your compensation metrics:
        </p>
        
        <h3>1. Regular Dayshift Earnings Formula</h3>
        <p>
          Your baseline compensation for standard dayshift hours:
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Regular Earnings} = \\text{Base Rate} \\times \\text{Regular Hours}\\)"}
        </p>

        <h3>2. Shift Differential Premium Rates</h3>
        <p>
          Differentials are calculated in one of two ways:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Flat Rate Premium ($/hr):</strong> An additional flat dollar amount is added to your base hourly rate:
            <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-4) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
              {"\\(\\text{Shift Rate} = \\text{Base Rate} + \\text{Flat Premium}\\)"}
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Percentage Premium (%):</strong> An additional percentage is added to your base hourly rate:
            <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-4) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
              {"\\(\\text{Shift Rate} = \\text{Base Rate} \\times (1 + \\frac{\\text{Percentage Premium}}{100})\\)"}
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>3. Total Gross Earnings & Net Take-Home</h3>
        <p>
          Summing all standard and premium sources yields your total gross pay:
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Total Gross Pay} = \\text{Regular Earnings} + \\text{Shift 1 Earnings} + \\text{Shift 2 Earnings}\\)"}
        </p>
        <p>
          To find your actual take-home cash after tax withholdings (T%):
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Net Take-Home Pay} = \\text{Total Gross Pay} \\times (1 - \\frac{\\text{Tax Rate (T)}}{100})\\)"}
        </p>

        <h3>4. Blended Effective Hourly Rate</h3>
        <p>
          Your blended hourly rate indicates your average earning power per hour worked across all standard and premium hours:
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Blended Hourly Rate} = \\frac{\\text{Total Gross Pay}}{\\text{Regular Hours} + \\text{Shift 1 Hours} + \\text{Shift 2 Hours}}\\)"}
        </p>

        <h2>Example Scenario Analysis</h2>
        <p>
          Suppose you earn a regular base rate of $20.00/hr. In one week, you work 40 standard dayshift hours, 12 night shift hours (with a $3.50/hr flat premium), and 8 weekend hours (with a 10% premium). Your estimated tax rate is 20%.
        </p>
        <p>
          The calculator will compute:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Regular Dayshift Earnings:</strong> {"\\(\\$20.00 \\times 40 = \\mathbf{\\$800.00}\\)"}
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Shift 1 (Night Shift):</strong> {"\\((\\$20.00 + \\$3.50) \\times 12 = \\mathbf{\\$282.00}\\)"} (hourly rate: $23.50/hr)
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Shift 2 (Weekend Shift):</strong> {"\\((\\$20.00 \\times 1.10) \\times 8 = \\mathbf{\\$176.00}\\)"} (hourly rate: $22.00/hr)
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Total Gross Pay:</strong> {"\\(\\$800 + \\$282 + \\$176 = \\mathbf{\\$1,258.00}\\)"}
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Net Take-Home Pay:</strong> {"\\(\\$1,258.00 \\times (1 - 0.20) = \\mathbf{\\$1,006.40}\\)"} (Taxes: $251.60)
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Blended Hourly Rate:</strong> {"\\(\\frac{\\$1,258.00}{60 \\text{ hours}} = \\mathbf{\\$20.97 \\text{ / hour}}\\)"} (a 4.83% increase over your base hourly rate)
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ Section -->
      <div class="calculator-faq-section" style="margin-top: var(--space-10); border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border); padding-top: var(--space-8);">
        <h2 style="font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">Shift Differential FAQs</h2>
        
        <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--space-4);">
          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);" open>
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">What is shift differential pay and how does it work?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              Shift differential pay is additional compensation hourly employees receive for working shifts outside standard business hours (such as nights, weekends, or holidays). It works by adding a flat premium ($/hr) or a percentage rate increase to your base hourly wage for those specific hours.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);">
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">What is the difference between a flat-rate and a percentage-based shift differential?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              A flat-rate differential adds a fixed dollar amount to your hourly wage (e.g. an extra <strong>$3.50 / hour</strong>). A percentage-based differential adds a percentage of your base wage (e.g. an extra <strong>10%</strong>). If your base wage increases, a percentage-based differential automatically increases, whereas a flat-rate differential remains constant.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);">
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">Which industries commonly offer shift differential pay?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              Shift differentials are common in industries that operate 24/7 or have extended business hours. These include healthcare (nurses, hospital staff), manufacturing, logistics & warehousing, customer support call centers, and hospitality.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);">
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">How does shift differential affect overtime pay calculations?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              Under FLSA rules, shift differentials must be included in your "regular rate of pay" when calculating overtime. If you earn a differential, your overtime rate (1.5x) must be calculated based on your blended regular rate for that workweek, not just your baseline dayshift rate.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);">
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">Is shift differential pay taxable?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              Yes. Shift differential pay is considered standard taxable income. It is subject to federal, state, and local income taxes, as well as FICA withholdings (Social Security and Medicare), just like your regular hourly wages.
            </p>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  .calculator-page-container {
    max-width: 1000px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-4);
  }

  .prose h2 {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    font-weight: 800;
    margin-top: var(--space-8);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    color: var(--color-text-base);
  }

  .prose h3 {
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    margin-top: var(--space-5);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    color: var(--color-text-base);
  }

  .prose p {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }

  .prose ul, .prose ol {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
  }

  .prose li {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }
</style>
